<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <!--
      Required for the QtWebEngine HUD subprocess to work under Hardened
      Runtime. QtWebEngine bundles a Chromium renderer (V8 JS engine).
      On Apple Silicon, V8 allocates its CodeRange with MAP_JIT (the
      only macOS-supported way to get concurrent W+X memory under
      hardware-enforced W^X), which requires this specific entitlement.
      Without allow-jit the renderer crashes immediately at boot with
      "V8 process OOM (Failed to reserve virtual memory for CodeRange)"
      and the HUD subprocess loads to a blank page — fires loadFinished
      with ok=False, no JS runs, no React mounts, no toast ever shows.
      `allow-unsigned-executable-memory` (above) is NOT a substitute on
      Apple Silicon — that grants W^X with explicit page-flips, but V8
      uses MAP_JIT exclusively on arm64. This bit Jhoanna 2026-05-15
      after the v2.10 HUD pywebview→Qt migration; pre-Qt the HUD ran
      in-process and reused the agent's Python interpreter so V8 never
      came into play.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
